tweet: Do faster VTs correlate with smaller circuits (and slow VTs big circuits)?  Comment with references also, please! #ablateVT

tweet: Do faster VTs correlate with smaller circuits (and slow VTs big circuits)?  Comment with references also, please! #ablateVT

tweet: I think it's an unacceptable solution that webhooks should rely on cert-manager for cert management. k8s itself needs to solve this problem. Not everything cert-manager does, but just issuing a self signed cert for webhooks.
reply:
@ibuildthecloud Speaking of which, it's also infuriating that you specify the ca as a line in the webhook manifest rather than link it to a cm/secret ref that contains it.

It comes really close to breaking the declarative promise if you want the cert managed by something other than human.

tweet: I think it's an unacceptable solution that webhooks should rely on cert-manager for cert management. k8s itself needs to solve this problem. Not everything cert-manager does, but just issuing a self signed cert for webhooks.
reply:
@ibuildthecloud We decided to go for managing inside of our Operator (https://t.co/lDTheIVY4z), and honestly I'm ok with the k8s decision.
Traffic must be encrypted, k8s offers CSR API to generate your own if handled by your webhook is a no go: that's the kube building blocks logic.

tweet: @markdeneve It also makes failure boundaries weird.  Before you could kill a controller with no impact.  Now that you have a webhook you have to be careful because it's more impactful.  So you really should separate webhook from controller but many don't.
reply: @ibuildthecloud @markdeneve I see this problem periodically in our managed Kubernetes product at DigitalOcean: users set up a webhook with a FailurePolicy of "Fail". tweet:
k3s Update

k8s 1.15 support is just about ready (just ironing out some bumps with the CI scripts).  This k8s version took longer to get out but it's because we spent a lot of time trying to figure out how to bring back a lot of k8s features with marginal overhead. 1/5
reply:
So what you'll see now is that the major changes in k3s' k8s version is:
* No in tree cloud providers
* No in tree storage drivers
* Optimized openapi packaging (40mb->190kb)
That means all admission controllers (including PSP) and alpha features are in k3s now. 2/5
